{  
  "response_text": "The mean environmental value deviation initiates at 0.0000, indicating perfect alignment between agents' held environmental values and the environmental implications of their milk choices at the outset. During the first five time steps, the metric undergoes a statistically significant rapid increase (Mann-Kendall tau=1.000, slope=2.840, p=0.027), rising sharply from 0 to approximately 12.8. The rate of increase moderates considerably between steps 5 and 9 (slope=0.109), with values climbing from roughly 12.5 to 13.0. By step 10, the trajectory approaches 13.3, reaching a maximum value of 13.4756 at step 13.\n\nFollowing this peak, the metric transitions into a prolonged plateau phase. From step 15 through step 32, values stabilize within a narrow range of 13.4153 to 13.4543, exhibiting no statistically significant directional trend. The final measurement at step 32 registers 13.4186, with the overall series averaging 12.6015 across all 33 time steps. The median value of 13.4302 indicates that the majority of the simulation duration maintains this elevated deviation level.\n\nThis trajectory demonstrates that the initial alignment between consumer environmental values and milk consumption choices deteriorates rapidly during the early transition period. Within the first 10-13 time steps, a substantial gap emerges and stabilizes at approximately 13.4 units, persisting throughout the remainder of the simulation. The system exhibits strong path dependency, as the high-deviation equilibrium becomes entrenched once established, with only minor fluctuations (less than 0.05 units) occurring during the plateau phase.\n\nFor decision makers, these findings suggest that the window for effective behavioral intervention is constrained to the initial 10-13 time steps of market transition. Once the deviation stabilizes around step 13-15, the misalignment between environmental values and consumption patterns becomes resistant to natural market correction, indicating that passive adoption models may perpetuate environmentally suboptimal choices. Proactive policies targeting the early phase—when habit formation and social influence mechanisms are most active—are essential to prevent the system from locking into a persistent high-deviation state where consumer choices systematically diverge from their stated environmental values."  
}

